  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence/core_explanation/1",
      "kind": "core_explanation",
      "conceptId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence",
      "title": "Equivalent Fractions — core idea",
      "content": "Two fractions a/b and c/d are equivalent if they represent the same quantity; this holds exactly when a×d = b×c, and is generated by multiplying (or dividing) both numerator and denominator by the same nonzero integer. Equivalence is a multiplicative relationship, not an additive one.",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.arith.fraction-equivalence.md",
        "startLine": 9,
        "endLine": 33
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence/learning_objective/1",
      "kind": "learning_objective",
      "conceptId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence",
      "title": "Learning Objective",
      "content": "A student who achieves mastery demonstrates that two fractions are equivalent when multiplying both numerator and denominator by the same nonzero integer, AND can generate equivalent fractions with a specified denominator, AND can verify equivalence using cross-multiplication. NOT merely recognising that \"1/2 and 2/4 look related\" or listing equivalents by repeated doubling. A student who generates equivalents mechanically (×2 only, or by guess) but cannot explain why the value is unchanged, or who uses additive reasoning (adds the same number to top and bottom), has NOT achieved mastery.\n\n**Accuracy threshold:** 85% across generation, verification, and classification tasks.\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.arith.fraction-equivalence.md",
        "startLine": 33,
        "endLine": 41
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence/misconception/MC-1",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence",
      "title": "— Adding Same Number to Numerator and Denominator Creates Equivalents",
      "content": "### MC-1 — Adding Same Number to Numerator and Denominator Creates Equivalents\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student generates 2/4 from 1/3 by adding 1 to both, or generates 4/7 from 3/6 by adding 1. States \"add the same number to top and bottom.\"\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** P41 after \"make a fraction equivalent to 1/3\" (DB-2; TA-C01).\n\n**Root cause:** Symmetry heuristic — students correctly apply \"same operation to both sides\" from equation-solving but conflate multiplication and addition as equally valid symmetric operations on fractions.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 (expose additive belief) → P28 (conflict: 1/3 ≈ 0.333 ≠ 2/4 = 0.500) → P29 (pause) → P30 (bridge: adding changes ratio; multiplying scales both parts together) → P31 (install correct rule: multiply) → P32 (three consolidation problems)\n\n**S6-safe path:** Omit P28; route through P30 directly with concrete strips showing unequal coverage when addition is applied.\n\n**MAMR status:** FOUNDATIONAL for MC-2. MC-1 must be cleared before MC-2 repair begins. Rationale: MC-2 repair involves cross-multiplication on non-simplified fractions; students carrying MC-1 will generate wrong \"equivalents\" to compare, making MC-2 repair incoherent.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-1"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.arith.fraction-equivalence.md",
        "startLine": 5,
        "endLine": 21
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence/misconception/MC-2",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence",
      "title": "— Only Simplified Fractions Are Valid / Equivalent",
      "content": "### MC-2 — Only Simplified Fractions Are Valid / Equivalent\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student accepts 3/4 as the \"only real\" fraction for that value; rejects 6/8 as \"not a proper fraction\" or \"a different fraction\" because it is not in lowest terms.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** P41 \"Is 6/8 equivalent to 3/4?\" (DB-2; TA-C01).\n\n**Root cause:** School instruction emphasises \"always simplify your answer,\" which students interpret as: the simplified form is the fraction; all other forms are incorrect or inferior.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 (expose belief) → P28 (conflict: cross-multiplication confirms 6/8 = 3/4 by definition) → P30 (bridge: simplification finds the simplest name; all names for the same value are valid) → P31 (install: equivalent fractions are multiple names for one quantity) → P33 (discrimination training: {(3/4, 6/8) → equivalent} vs {(3/4, 5/8) → not equivalent})\n\n**S6-safe path:** Omit P28; use P07 (number line) to show 6/8 and 3/4 land at the same point before introducing P30.\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent of other misconceptions.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-2"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.arith.fraction-equivalence.md",
        "startLine": 21,
        "endLine": 37
      }
    },
