    {
      "assetId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence/mastery_probe/1",
      "kind": "mastery_probe",
      "conceptId": "math.arith.fraction-equivalence",
      "title": "Assessment Battery",
      "content": "---\n\n**AB-1 — Classification Battery** (P74-pattern)\n\nClassify each pair as equivalent or not. Show cross-multiplication working.\n\n| Item | Pair | Verdict |\n|------|------|---------|\n| a | 2/3 and 6/9 | equivalent — 2×9=18=3×6 |\n| b | 3/5 and 4/6 | not equivalent — 3×6=18 ≠ 5×4=20 |\n| c | 5/8 and 15/24 | equivalent — 5×24=120=8×15 |\n| d | 1/4 and 3/16 | not equivalent — 1×16=16 ≠ 4×3=12 |\n\nPass: 4/4 with correct cross-multiplication shown.  \nFail routing: additive errors on any item → MC-1; rejection of c as \"not equivalent because 15/24 isn't simplified\" → MC-2.\n\n---\n\n**AB-2 — Boundary Probe** (P75-pattern)\n\n\"Is 0/5 equivalent to 0/100? Explain. Is 5/0 a valid fraction? Why or why not?\"\n\nPass criteria: Yes, 0/5 = 0/100 (both equal zero; cross-mult: 0×100 = 5×0 = 0). No, 5/0 is undefined (division by zero).\n\n---\n\n**AB-3 — Generation Probe** (P77-pattern)\n\n\"Generate four fractions all equivalent to 3/8, using a different multiplier each time.\"\n\nPass criteria: 6/16, 9/24, 12/32, 15/40 (or any ×k equivalents with k=2,3,4,5). All verifiable by cross-multiplication.\n\n---\n\n**AB-4 — Explanation Probe** (P78-pattern)\n\n\"Explain in one sentence why 6/10 and 9/15 are equivalent.\"\n\nPass criteria: References equal cross-products (6×15=90=10×9), or notes both equal 3/5 via multiplication by 2/2 and 3/3, or states the multiplicative relationship explicitly.\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-1",
        "MC-2"
      ],
